"# Chapter 14 — Grade 14: Calculus II

## The Integral and the Infinite Series

### History & how it developed

After Newton and Leibniz gave us the derivative—the mathematics of instantaneous change—the question turned around: if we know the rate, can we recover the total? If velocity is the derivative of position, what operation undoes that and gives us position back? The answer was the *integral*, and it opened a door that has never closed.

Archimedes, two thousand years before calculus had a name, approximated the area under a parabola by summing thinner and thinner slices. He called it the \"method of exhaustion\"—exhaust the shape with rectangles until there's no gap left. Newton and Leibniz made it formal: they connected the integral to the derivative (the Fundamental Theorem), invented notation (the long ∫ that still decorates every calculus page), and turned area-under-curve into a reversible operation. Leibniz wrote his integrals as sums of infinitely many infinitesimal pieces; Newton saw them as the inverse of fluxions. Both were right.

Then came the techniques—substitution, parts, partial fractions—each a lock-pick for a different family of functions. And then the applications: area, volume, arc length, work, probability. The integral became the tool for *accumulation*—anything that piles up continuously, from the distance a car travels to the charge stored in a capacitor.

Alongside the integral grew the mathematics of the infinite: sequences that march toward a limit, series that sum infinitely many terms. Does 1 + 1/2 + 1/4 + 1/8 + … have a finite sum? (Yes: 2.) Does 1 + 1/2 + 1/3 + 1/4 + … ? (No: it diverges.) Brook Taylor, in 1715, showed that smooth functions could be written as infinite polynomials—Taylor series—turning transcendental mystery into algebraic addition. Leonhard Euler used series to compute π to ridiculous precision. The infinite became *tractable*.

Calculus II is where the derivative's twin—integration—gets its full toolkit, and where the infinite becomes something you can hold in your hand and compute with.

### Uses & utility in the world

Integration is the mathematics of *totals*. Physics uses it everywhere: the work done by a force over a distance, the center of mass of an irregular object, the probability that a random variable falls in a range. Engineering uses it to compute moments, stresses, fluid flow. Economics uses it to find consumer surplus from a demand curve. Biology uses it to model population growth from a rate equation.

The techniques—substitution, integration by parts, trigonometric substitution, partial fractions—are not ornamental. They're the lock-picks that open the integrals you'll actually meet. Substitution handles composition; parts handles products; trig substitution handles radicals; partial fractions crack rational functions into pieces you can integrate term-by-term.

Series let you *approximate*. A computer can't calculate sin(x) directly—silicon doesn't know what sine *means*. But it can add polynomials, so it uses the Taylor series: sin(x) ≈ x - x³/6 + x⁵/120 - … . Every scientific calculator, every physics simulation, every 3D rendering pipeline uses series under the hood. They turn the transcendental into the polynomial, the infinite into the finite-but-accurate.

Arc length, surface area, and volume of revolution—these are the *geometry* of integration, where you see calculus draw and measure shapes that Euclid never imagined.

### What we'll cover and why

We'll build the integral from the ground up: Riemann sums (the rectangles Archimedes imagined), the Fundamental Theorem (why antiderivatives compute area), and definite vs. indefinite integration. Then we'll learn the *techniques*—the algebraic moves that transform a hard integral into an easy one.

We'll compute area between curves, volumes by slicing and by shells, arc length, and surface area. We'll meet *improper integrals*—integrals over infinite intervals or with infinite discontinuities—and learn when they converge.

Then we'll turn to the infinite: sequences and their limits, series and convergence tests (the integral test, comparison tests, ratio test, alternating series test). We'll build Taylor and Maclaurin series, see how to approximate functions with polynomials, and estimate the error. We'll end with *power series*—functions built from infinite sums—and their intervals of convergence.

Every example is a Scheme program you can run. We'll draw Riemann sums filling under a curve, plot partial sums of a Taylor series converging to the target function, and visualize solids of revolution.

### Its utility in Motoi

The runtime moves dots on a 4096×4096 canvas. Integration is how she measures what those dots enclose: the area under a plotted function, the volume of a shape spun around an axis, the arc length of a curve she's drawn. When she animates a particle along a path, integration computes the distance traveled. When she models a spring or a pendulum, integration recovers position from velocity.

Series are how she *computes transcendentals*. She doesn't have a sine oracle—she has addition and multiplication. So `calc/sin` and `calc/cos` use Taylor series under the hood, and she can *see* the partial sums converging to the true curve on the canvas.

When she fits a function to data, she's minimizing an integral (least-squares error). When she generates a smooth curve through control points, she's solving an integral equation (splines). When she shades a gradient, she's sampling a cumulative distribution—an integral.

We call it Calculus II, but we're really teaching her to *accumulate and approximate*—to sum infinitely many pieces, to measure shapes, to turn the infinite into the drawable.

---

## Topic 1: Riemann Sums and the Definite Integral

### History & the idea

Archimedes wanted to find the area under a parabola. He couldn't integrate—he lived 2,000 years too early—but he could *approximate*. He filled the region with rectangles, computed their total area, then made the rectangles thinner. As the width shrank, the approximation improved. He called it exhaustion: exhaust the error until none remains.

Bernhard Riemann, in the 1850s, formalized this. A *Riemann sum* chops the interval [a, b] into n subintervals, builds a rectangle on each (height = f at some sample point, width = Δx), and adds their areas. As n → ∞, the sum approaches a limit—the *definite integral* ∫ₐᵇ f(x) dx, the exact area under the curve.

### Uses in the world

Riemann sums are how numerical integration works. When you can't find an antiderivative (or don't want to), you approximate: chop the domain, sample, sum. GPS receivers integrate acceleration to get velocity, velocity to get position—digitally, with Riemann sums. Climate models integrate differential equations the same way.

### What we'll cover

We'll compute left, right, and midpoint Riemann sums by hand and by Scheme. We'll watch the approximation improve as n grows. We'll define the definite integral as the limit, and use `calc/riemann-sum` and `calc/integral` to compute exact and approximate areas.

### In Motoi

When the runtime shades the area under a plotted function, she's drawing a Riemann sum—bars stacking up until they fill the shape. `calc/riemann-sum` is the verb that does it, and `plot/` renders the bars on the canvas so you can watch the approximation tighten.

---

### Example 1: Left Riemann sum, 4 rectangles, f(x) = x², [0, 2]

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define a 0)
(define b 2)
(define n 4)
(define dx (/ (- b a) n))

(define (left-sum i acc)
  (if (>= i n)
      acc
      (let* ((xi (+ a (* i dx)))
             (height (f xi))
             (area (* height dx)))
        (left-sum (+ i 1) (+ acc area)))))

(define result (left-sum 0 0))

(display \"Left Riemann sum, n=4: \")
(display result)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run through interpreter, print output to console, render no visual (pure numeric). -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `Left Riemann sum, n=4: 3.5`]

---

### Example 2: Right Riemann sum, same setup

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define a 0)
(define b 2)
(define n 4)
(define dx (/ (- b a) n))

(define (right-sum i acc)
  (if (>= i n)
      acc
      (let* ((xi (+ a (* (+ i 1) dx)))
             (height (f xi))
             (area (* height dx)))
        (right-sum (+ i 1) (+ acc area)))))

(define result (right-sum 0 0))

(display \"Right Riemann sum, n=4: \")
(display result)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print output. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `Right Riemann sum, n=4: 5.5`]

---

### Example 3: Midpoint Riemann sum, n=4

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define a 0)
(define b 2)
(define n 4)
(define dx (/ (- b a) n))

(define (midpoint-sum i acc)
  (if (>= i n)
      acc
      (let* ((xi (+ a (* (+ i 0.5) dx)))
             (height (f xi))
             (area (* height dx)))
        (midpoint-sum (+ i 1) (+ acc area)))))

(define result (midpoint-sum 0 0))

(display \"Midpoint Riemann sum, n=4: \")
(display result)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `Midpoint Riemann sum, n=4: 4.25`]

The exact integral ∫₀² x² dx = 8/3 ≈ 2.6667. Midpoint is closest!

