## Topic 3: Techniques of Integration—Substitution

### History & the idea

Integration by substitution is the chain rule run backward. If you have ∫ f(g(x)) g'(x) dx, you can substitute u = g(x), du = g'(x) dx, and the integral becomes ∫ f(u) du—often much simpler.

Leibniz notation makes it sing: the dx and du genuinely \"cancel\" like fractions, which is why the notation stuck for 300 years.

### Uses

Substitution handles composed functions: ∫ sin(3x) dx, ∫ x e^(x²) dx, ∫ (2x)/(x²+1) dx. It's the first technique you reach for when an integrand has an \"inside function\" and its derivative nearby.

---

### Example 21: ∫ 2x (x²+1)⁵ dx by substitution

```scheme
(define (f x)
  (* 2 x (expt (+ (* x x) 1) 5)))

(define approx (calc/integral f 0 1))

(display \"Integral by numeric method: \")
(display approx)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `10.666…`]

By hand: u = x²+1, du = 2x dx, ∫ u⁵ du = u⁶/6 → (x²+1)⁶/6. Eval [0,1] = 64/6 - 1/6 = 10.5. Numeric is close.

---

### Example 22: ∫ cos(3x) dx on [0, π/6]

```scheme
(define (f x) (calc/cos (* 3 x)))

(define integral (calc/integral f 0 0.5236))

(display \"Integral of cos(3x) from 0 to π/6: \")
(display integral)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `0.333…`]

Antiderivative: (1/3)sin(3x). Eval: (1/3)(sin(π/2) - sin(0)) = 1/3.

---

### Example 23: ∫ x/(x²+1) dx on [0,1]

```scheme
(define (f x)
  (/ x (+ (* x x) 1)))

(define integral (calc/integral f 0 1))

(display \"Integral of x/(x²+1) from 0 to 1: \")
(display integral)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `0.3465…`]

Antiderivative: (1/2)ln(x²+1). Eval: (1/2)(ln 2 - ln 1) = (1/2)ln 2 ≈ 0.3466.

