## Topic 4: Integration by Parts

### History & the product rule inverted

Integration by parts is the product rule run backward:
(uv)' = u'v + uv' → uv' = (uv)' - u'v → ∫ u dv = uv - ∫ v du.

It handles products where substitution fails: ∫ x eˣ dx, ∫ x sin(x) dx, ∫ ln(x) dx (write ln(x) as 1·ln(x)).

### Uses

Physics: integrating x·force(x), t·velocity(t). Probability: moments E[X] = ∫ x·f(x) dx. Parts is the tool for products of \"different types\"—polynomial times exponential, polynomial times trig.

---

### Example 26: ∫ x eˣ dx on [0,1] numerically

```scheme
(define (f x)
  (* x (calc/exp x)))

(define integral (calc/integral f 0 1))

(display \"Integral of x e^x from 0 to 1: \")
(display integral)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `1.0`]

By parts: u=x, dv=eˣ dx → du=dx, v=eˣ → ∫ x eˣ = x eˣ - ∫ eˣ = x eˣ - eˣ = eˣ(x-1). Eval [0,1]: e(0) - (-1) = 1.

---

### Example 27: ∫ x sin(x) dx on [0,π]

```scheme
(define (f x)
  (* x (calc/sin x)))

(define integral (calc/integral f 0 3.14159))

(display \"Integral of x sin(x) from 0 to π: \")
(display integral)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `3.1416…`]

By parts: u=x, dv=sin dx → uv - ∫ v du = -x cos + ∫ cos = -x cos + sin. Eval [0,π]: -π(-1) + 0 - 0 = π.

---

### Example 28: ∫ ln(x) dx on [1,e]

```scheme
(define (f x) (calc/log x))

(define integral (calc/integral f 1 2.71828))

(display \"Integral of ln(x) from 1 to e: \")
(display integral)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `1.0`]

By parts: u=ln(x), dv=dx → uv - ∫ v du = x ln(x) - ∫ x (1/x) = x ln(x) - x. Eval [1,e]: (e·1 - e) - (0 - 1) = 1.

---

### Example 29: ∫ x² eˣ dx on [0,1]—parts twice

```scheme
(define (f x)
  (* x x (calc/exp x)))

(define integral (calc/integral f 0 1))

(display \"Integral of x² e^x from 0 to 1: \")
(display integral)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `0.7183…`]

First parts: u=x², dv=eˣ → x²eˣ - 2∫ x eˣ. Second: ∫ x eˣ = eˣ(x-1). Final: eˣ(x²-2x+2). Eval [0,1]: e(1) - 2 = e - 2 ≈ 0.7183.

