## Topic 5: Area Between Curves

### History & the idea

Once you can integrate to find area under *one* curve, you can find area *between* two curves by subtraction: ∫ₐᵇ (f(x) - g(x)) dx, where f ≥ g on [a,b]. Archimedes did this for parabolas; Fermat extended it to algebraic curves.

### Uses

Economics: consumer surplus is the area between a demand curve and a price line. Physics: work done by a variable force between two displacement curves.

---

### Example 30: Area between y=x² and y=x on [0,1]

```scheme
(define (f x) x)
(define (g x) (* x x))

(define area (calc/integral (lambda (x) (- (f x) (g x))) 0 1))

(display \"Area between y=x and y=x² on [0,1]: \")
(display area)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `0.1666…`]

By hand: ∫(x - x²) = x²/2 - x³/3. Eval [0,1]: 1/2 - 1/3 = 1/6.

---

### Example 31: Visualize the region between y=x and y=x²

```scheme
(define xs (map (lambda (i) (* i 0.05)) (iota 21)))

(define ys-line (map (lambda (x) x) xs))
(define ys-parabola (map (lambda (x) (* x x)) xs))

(define pts-line (map list xs ys-line))
(define pts-parabola (map list xs ys-parabola))

(define p (plot/with
            (plot/line pts-line)
            (plot/line pts-parabola)))

(plot/render-svg p)
```

<!-- BUILD: render SVG on Cartesian grid [0,1]×[0,1], two curves, shaded region between would be visible if we had fill—here just the bounding curves. -->

[VISUAL: Two curves: y=x (straight diagonal) and y=x² (parabola), enclosing a lens-shaped region.]

---

