## Topic 7: Arc Length and Surface Area

### History

The arc length formula—∫ √(1 + (dy/dx)²) dx—comes from Pythagoras applied to infinitesimal pieces. Surface area of revolution—∫ 2πy √(1+(dy/dx)²) dx—wraps the arc around the axis.

### Uses

Cable length in suspension bridges. Surface area of containers. Geodesics on curved surfaces.

---

### Example 38: Arc length of y=x² on [0,1]

```scheme
(define (f x) (* x x))

(define (integrand x)
  (let ((dydx (* 2 x)))
    (calc/sqrt (+ 1 (* dydx dydx)))))

(define arc-length (calc/integral integrand 0 1))

(display \"Arc length of y=x² on [0,1]: \")
(display arc-length)
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: `1.478…`]

---

