## Topic 8: Improper Integrals

### History

What if the interval is infinite, or the integrand blows up? Euler and Cauchy defined the *improper integral* as a limit: ∫₁^∞ 1/x² dx = lim_{b→∞} ∫₁ᵇ 1/x² dx. If the limit exists and is finite, the integral *converges*; otherwise it diverges.

### Uses

Probability: ∫₋∞^∞ of a PDF must be 1. Physics: potential energy at infinity. Signal processing: Fourier transforms.

---

### Example 41: ∫₁^∞ 1/x² dx

```scheme
(define (f x) (/ 1 (* x x)))

(define (approx-integral b)
  (calc/integral f 1 b))

(display \"∫₁¹⁰ 1/x²: \")
(display (approx-integral 10))
(newline)

(display \"∫₁¹⁰⁰ 1/x²: \")
(display (approx-integral 100))
(newline)

(display \"∫₁¹⁰⁰⁰ 1/x²: \")
(display (approx-integral 1000))
(newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: three values approaching 1.0]

Exact: -1/x from 1 to ∞ → 0 - (-1) = 1.

---

### Example 42: ∫₁^∞ 1/x dx diverges

