## Topic 11: Power Series and Taylor Series

### History & the infinite polynomial

A *power series* is Σ cₙ (x-a)ⁿ—a polynomial of infinite degree. Brook Taylor (1715) showed that smooth functions f(x) can be written as power series centered at a:

f(x) = f(a) + f'(a)(x-a) + f''(a)(x-a)²/2! + …

Maclaurin series (a=0) are the special case. Euler used them to compute e, π, logarithms. Newton used them to solve differential equations.

### Uses

Approximation: sin(x) ≈ x - x³/6 + x⁵/120 is how your calculator works. Differential equations: solve y' = y as y = 1 + x + x²/2! + … = eˣ. Physics: perturbation theory.

### In Motoi

When she plots `calc/sin`, the verb uses a Taylor series internally. When she animates a pendulum, she can linearize (first-order Taylor) or keep higher terms for accuracy. The infinite becomes the computable.

---

### Example 57: Taylor series for eˣ at x=0

```scheme
(define (factorial n)
  (if (<= n 1) 1 (* n (factorial (- n 1)))))

(define (taylor-exp x n)
  (fold + 0
        (map (lambda (k) (/ (expt x k) (factorial k)))
             (iota n 0))))

(define x 1.0)

(display \"e^1, 5 terms: \") (display (taylor-exp x 5)) (newline)
(display \"e^1, 10 terms: \") (display (taylor-exp x 10)) (newline)
(display \"e^1, exact: \") (display (calc/exp x)) (newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: 2.708…, 2.71828…, 2.71828… .]

---

### Example 58: Taylor series for sin(x) at x=0

```scheme
(define (factorial n)
  (if (<= n 1) 1 (* n (factorial (- n 1)))))

(define (taylor-sin x n)
  (fold + 0
        (map (lambda (k)
               (let ((sign (expt -1 k))
                     (pow (expt x (+ (* 2 k) 1)))
                     (fact (factorial (+ (* 2 k) 1))))
                 (/ (* sign pow) fact)))
             (iota n 0))))

(define x 1.0)

(display \"sin(1), 3 terms: \") (display (taylor-sin x 3)) (newline)
(display \"sin(1), 5 terms: \") (display (taylor-sin x 5)) (newline)
(display \"sin(1), exact: \") (display (calc/sin x)) (newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: 0.8416…, 0.8414…, 0.8414… .]

---

### Example 59: Taylor series for cos(x)

```scheme
(define (factorial n)
  (if (<= n 1) 1 (* n (factorial (- n 1)))))

(define (taylor-cos x n)
  (fold + 0
        (map (lambda (k)
               (let ((sign (expt -1 k))
                     (pow (expt x (* 2 k)))
                     (fact (factorial (* 2 k))))
                 (/ (* sign pow) fact)))
             (iota n 0))))

(define x 1.5708)

(display \"cos(π/2), 5 terms: \") (display (taylor-cos x 5)) (newline)
(display \"cos(π/2), exact: \") (display (calc/cos x)) (newline)
```

<!-- BUILD: run, print. -->

[VISUAL: Console output: both ≈ 0.0]

---

### Example 60: Plot Taylor partial sums for sin(x)

```scheme
(define (factorial n)
  (if (<= n 1) 1 (* n (factorial (- n 1)))))

(define (taylor-sin x n)
  (fold + 0
        (map (lambda (k)
               (let ((sign (expt -1 k))
                     (pow (expt x (+ (* 2 k) 1)))
                     (fact (factorial (+ (* 2 k) 1))))
                 (/ (* sign pow) fact)))
             (iota n 0))))

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (* i 0.1)) (iota 61 -30)))

(define ys-exact (map calc/sin xs))
(define ys-3 (map (lambda (x) (taylor-sin x 3)) xs))
(define ys-5 (map (lambda (x) (taylor-sin x 5)) xs))

(define pts-exact (map list xs ys-exact))
(define pts-3 (map list xs ys-3))
(define pts-5 (map list xs ys-5))

(define p (plot/with
            (plot/line pts-exact)
            (plot/line pts-3)
            (plot/line pts-5)))

(plot/render-svg p)
```

<!-- BUILD: render SVG on Cartesian grid [-3,3]×[-2,2], three curves: exact sine (smooth), 3-term Taylor (cubic), 5-term Taylor (better fit near 0, diverges farther out). -->

[VISUAL: The exact sine oscillates smoothly. The 3-term approximation matches near x=0 but curves away. The 5-term stays close longer, then diverges.]

